n soul must first come to an experience of non-dualistic, mind-only metaphysics, and after attaining this wisdom, promote moral activism. Engaged Emancipation is a wide-ranging consideration of this work and the philosophical and spiritual questions it addresses by philosophers, Sanskritists, and scholars of religion, literature, and science. Contributors allow readers to walk with Rāma as his melancholy and angst transform into connectivity, peace, and spiritual equipoise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHindu philosophy. 0aMokosa. 0aMokṣa. 0aMokṣa. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Yoga. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / Sacred Writings.2bisacsh1 aBregman, Garth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakrabarti, Arindam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakrabarti, Arindam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChapple, Christopher Key, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapple, Christopher Key, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFort, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanesathasan, Menaha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhosal, Pranati, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKey Chapple, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacKenzie, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNarasimha, Roddam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTimalsina, Sthaneshwar, econtributor.4ctb4https:/